===Etymology===
Comes from [[w:Arabic language|Arabic]][[Category:Arabic derivations]] ﺮﺏﻥﺀ ''khanbar'' (the 'kh' representing a fricative aspirant), meaning "ambergris." The ambergris, of animal origin, somehow became confused with the fossil resin, of vegetable origin, so the [[w:French language|French]][[category:French derivations]] language differentiated them as ''ambre gris'', grey amber and ''ambre jaune'', yellow amber. [[English language|English]] adopted this differentiation in the form of respectively, ambergris and amber. The [[w:German language|German]][[Category:German derivations]] language adopted respectively, ''Amber'' (or ''Ambra'')  and ''Bernstein''.

